\par NOTES
\par Corticotropin (ACTH) like substances elaborated by malignant tissue, particularly in the lung, pancreas or prostate, may also lead to Cushing's disease
\par 
\par 
\par Indications:
\par \bullet  To differentiate  adrenal hyperplasia and adrenal adenoma from adrenal carcinoma and Addison's disease
\par 
\par \bullet  To diagnose adrenal insufficiency
\par 
\par SAMPLE REQUIREMENT
\par Serum 
\par 
\par COMMON FINDINGS
\par A normal response to ACTH - a rise of plasma cortisol of 6 mcg/dL above the basal level
\par 
\par NORMAL VALUE
\par Three criteria : 
\par \bullet  Basal cortisol - at least 5 micro g/dL
\par \bullet  Incremental increase after Cortrosyn injection - at least 7 micro g/dL
\par \bullet  Final serum cortisol - at least 16 micro g/dL at 30 minutes, 18 micro g/dL at 60 minutes or cortisol increase of more than 10 microg/dL
\par 
\par 
\par \bullet  Aldosterone increase - more than 5 ng/dL over baseline
\par 
\par 
\par METHOD
\par \bullet  Estimate basal plasma cortisol level, urinary 17 ketosteroids (17 KS) and ketogenic steroids (KGS) over 24 hours
\par 
\par \bullet  Give 25 units of ACTH diluted in 100 mL of N saline IV lasting for over 8 hours (or cosyntropin is given 0.25 mg 1M or IV )
\par 
\par \bullet  Collect serum samples after 30 and 60 minutes
\par 
\par \bullet  Then estimate plasma cortisol, 24 hour urinary 17 KS and KGS including the period of infusion 
\par 
\par \bullet  Alternately cortrosyn (an ACTH analogue) can be given at a dose of 0.25 mg IM or IV in adults or 0.125 mg in children less than 2 years
\par 
\par \bullet  Blood is collected at time 0, 30, and 60 minutes for cortisol and aldosterone
\par 
\par CONDITIONS/DISEASES
\par \bullet  Addison's disease (primary adrenal insufficiency) - neither cortisol nor aldosterone increases over baseline
\par 
\par \bullet  Secondary adrenal insufficiency - caused by pituitary insufficiency or suppression by exogenous steroids - cortisol does not change but aldosterone increases
\par 
\par Elevated in:
\par (plasma cortisol, 24 hour urinary 17 KS and KGS - post ACTH values elevated 2-7 times above the preinfusion levels)
\par \bullet  Adrenal hyperplasia
\par \bullet  Adrenal adenoma
\par \bullet  Cushing's syndrome
\par 
\par 
\par Negative in:
\par (No rise in plasma cortisol, 24 hour urinary 17 KS and KGS)
\par \bullet  Adrenal carcinoma
\par \bullet  Addison's disease 
\par \bullet  Secondary adrenal insufficiency
\par 
\par Synonyms:
\par \bullet  Adreno corticotropin stimulation test
